once familiar with) tries to worm his way out of the deal, when none other than that same smuggler appearing with his hairy apprentice and pulls him out of the Mexican stand-off. 'It is MY SHIP!' He bellowed. And the newly formed three stooges blast their way through bounty hunters. There you have it. The Solo Entrƒï. Sure beats suddenly dropping him on the falcon. Alas.. I'm no Abrams. And I'm pretty sure I'm sounding too full of myself here. But I really expected a little more. Just because it worked, it doesn't necessary make it as good by compressing all three parts back into one.(It cannot be a coincidence that this installment consists of the environments present in the original one. Audiences experienced the deserts of Tatooine, the frost of Hoth and the forestry of Endor) It is a fancy idea, I'm not gonna argue with that. But every other attempt to impress feels like one failed CPR after another. When the Empire Struck Back or when the Jedi Returned amongst others, they all followed the same simple story structure. The story held up several plots which are interdependent on the other and one cannot occur without the other happening. It's perfectly alright to repeat, however much more could have been done to intensify the subplots. For example, I would have loved that at a crucial moment, it is Leia who displayed the art of 'this are not the droids you're looking for'. I would also have preferred that audience aren't let in first on the reason why Solo will have a secret solo mission on his own, which is to distract his son. So many could-haves.. but all has beens. It was amazing back then, when one gradually discovered how Lucas mimed the entire Nazi machinery on-screen into science fiction. From the misnomer 'Stormtroopers', to their military structure and uniforms. Now, barely anything in the story is anywhere near inspiring. Hollywood has forgotten how to portray evil much less good. With the reportoire of works that he has had, there's no reason for Abram's sub-standard treatment of this story of old. He didn't even try. But he's done it now, rounding off the last set of the trilogy by making it nothing more then a hodge podge series of stories about father-killers. Either the idiot be him, or he's actually a flexible genius to not have Michael Bay-ed every show he directs. Because if anything, this latest piece of work could be a secret parody directed at the dearth of cinematic imagination and how poor audience expectations actually controls the direction of the Star Wars mythos. He at least effectively used the opening scenes of fallen Republic war machines to signify the detachment of the new series to the original stories many were once familiar with. It's a tough job because we must remember that there are varied segments of audiences. Those that missed all the episodes before, those that experienced the second series but not the first. And those in their 30s and 40s who were there since the genesis. On top of these, what was fascinating before may have fallen short because of what's currently hogging audience's and critics' interests. But regardless of these varied considerations, what is core to the business of cinematic magic shldn't have change. Therefore, I would still consider unforgivable that he has dropped the entire franchise into an abyss of uncertainty. Verdict: 1 out of 5 stars. Nothing remotely redeeming. Mentioned spoilers at the start but I assure you, there's not much more damage I can do from what it has already done to itself.This film and its actors show little sign of the punchiness and grit that is Star Wars Star Wars 2015 was, so I believed, supposed to be the follow up to the first Trilogy that included gritty stars such as Harrison Ford and Mark Hamill. True we did get a glimpse of the old Hans Solo and boy was he great. Not so the new wave of actors invading the Galaxy! When Luke Skywalker learnt to be a Jedi Knight, it took time and patience - and it was worth the wait! Not so the young pretenders! In the space of a short time they were able to become the Superheroes of Time and Space. The best actor, in my opinion - was the rugged, gutsy pilot, Poe Dameron, who only had a bit part in the film. Disappointing all round - including the outcome.a safe re-run of past well-performing brand names given a fresh lick of paint by talentless hacks in the service of corporate greed So I've been doing my damnedest to avoid The Force Awakens but was sufficiently bored today to get sucked into its gravitational field along with just about the entirety of the rest of the western hemisphere, it seems. The new Star Wars cash-in is a terribly dull, unoriginal, empty and uninspiring facsimile of a movie made by shareholder meetings and accountants brunches that I nearly walked out of more than once. There were no Jar-Jars and midichlorians in it, it's true, and we should be thankful for that, but there was nothing new in it to take their place, either: it added nothing whatsoever to the existing universe or overall story, and instead of moving it forward was - as many others have said already - for the most part simply a remake of the first film that started it all. Han and Leia looked frail and doddery and had almost nothing of substance to do - I would be surprised if Carrie Fisher's role required more than a day and a half of shooting, and Harrison Ford was apparently simply told 'look regretful once in awhile' and that was about it for the acting. I saw the film only hours ago and cannot recall even one single line of dialogue from it. None of the much-loved returning characters DID anything to remind you why you loved them in the first place, they were just wheeled onto the set, propped up with sticks and then wheeled back off to the nursing home again afterwards. And the new actors were all bland, characterless and immediately forgettable, with the possible exception of Adam Driver, who starts out very well but like the rest of the cast has nothing to do by the end and his character has become an inexplicably weak shadow of himself by then. The only flickers of enjoyment in the whole sorry affair came from nostalgia: the ruins of an AT-AT, half-covered by sand in the desert; the reappearance of the Millennium Falcon. All the rest was a safe re-run of past well-performing brand names given a fresh lick of paint by talentless hacks in the service of corporate greed, with no surprises and no discernible story requiring telling at the heart of it. I didn't quite feel my childhood was being raped in front of me, but I know it's the last Star Wars film I'll ever pay to see. I guess at least I got that hard-won knowledge out of the experience, but that is all.The Force Awakens: A New Hope Remixed The basic plot of The Force Awakens is heavily borrowed from A New Hope. JJ Abrams introduced new characters that are not really new. Everything in this new world is familiar. Whatever worked with the old Star Wars was copied and rehashed into the greatest hits of The Force Awakens. Rey is essentially the new Luke; Rey is the new comic relief here in place of Chewbacca; Poe, a pilot, is the new Han Solo; BB-8 is a cuter R2-D2. In this new movie, the Death Star is gone, but it was replaced by a bigger one - "The Star Killer". In place of Darth Vader is Kylo Ren. Visually, it is as epic as any Star Wars, but story-wise it is moronic. It is no better than any Avengers movie.Typical JJ Abrams Trash The movie was BADLY written horribly cast and had not only terrible acting but MASSIVE PLOT HOLES. Its simply a crappy remake of the original in Jar Jar Abrams style, he steals another person franchise, rips out elements he wants an then remakes all the other parts BADLY and the hype sells tickets. The problem is that Fanboys are TOO STUPID to stop paying to see CRAP with the SW title on it.The 30 years after trilogy sequels that should never had been made F*ck this Force Awakens ! I really-really love Star Wars universe, whatever many hardc