 performance in The Wolf of Wall Street. When I was looking at the trailers it definitely looked like the movie could be a lot of fun so I went into this with low expectations, due to the February release date but I was hopeful and I do enjoy a good heist/conman movie. *Minor Spoilers Ahead* Nicky (Will Smith) pulls some strings to get a table at a club and while he's at his table, an attractive woman named Jess (Margot Robbie) asks him to pretend to be her boyfriend to ward off some creepy guy at the bar. They get to talking and after a while, Nicky is invited up to her room. Just as things start to heat up, some man bursts in claiming to be her husband. Instead of panicking, Nicky cracks jokes, realizing almost immediately that they are setting him up. He leaves but follows Jess when she leaves the hotel. After telling her more about his family's past, he agrees to show her some moves and he begins to steal everything that she has on her. He lectures her on maintaining focus and to pay attention to detail and when there is nothing left to teach (or to steal) he leaves for New Orleans to set up a crime ring while the Super Bowl is going on. Jess tracks him down though and begs him to let her be part of his crew. He reluctantly agrees to and reveals he knew about her being there the whole time. The first thing that I want to say about this movie is that it feels slick and I mean that in a good way. The locations are stunning, the cinematography is beautiful and the movie takes full advantage of that. Focus radiates a sense of cool (helped along from the efforts of the cast)and you want to see what will happen next. Adding to the well-polished feeling is that the film moves at a pretty quick pace (especially in the first half). There are small flaws in the plot (more on that later) but the movie moves fast enough that you sense the creators were aware of this and knew that they needed to deliver a tight story to help it along. I got the feeling that there were some experienced people at the reigns and they knew what they needed to do to make this movie appealing which I would say they did in spades. I found the acting in this movie to be impressive. I would say this is the strongest Will has been in a while. I don't understand the hate around his acting but he did try something distinctive here, playing a more unlikable main character. He was funny and suave, he always is but he's occasionally given the chance to do something more and he performs well. It felt like he was giving it his all and I think that came through in his performance. I also walked away really impressed with Margot Robbie's performance. Her character of Jess isn't given much back story so it's up to her to carry her share without added depth and she really pulled it off. Getting past the fact that she's beautiful between this and The Wolf On Wall Street, she really comes across as a pro and someone who is talented beyond her years. I'm definitely looking forward to what she does next. I also want to credit Adrian Martinez and BD Wong for being very funny in their respective roles. Rodrigo Santoro gave a surprisingly subtle performance and Gerald McRaney is great but he's given probably the worst dialogue out of the group. He does his best to sell it but it doesn't always work. I see this movie split into two distinct halves. I thought the first half of this movie is really strong. There's two interesting characters you are introduced to that have excellent chemistry, the dialogue is funny and most importantly, it finds a way to subvert most of the heist/conman movie tropes. Nicky and Jess concentrate more on working on a small scale, poking fun that in every story it's always about "the big con." The low key action scenes find an ideal balance between fun and interesting and from scene to scene you have something different to have fun with(the Super Bowl con was my favourite). The second half is still good but it's decidedly weaker. It becomes more of a romantic comedy, targeting the relationships as opposed to the con. It works because of the strong acting but it moonwalks back into conventionality. It's not predictable but you know it's all going to have a happy ending. My other complaint is with the ending itself, it seems like they went with a couple of twists too many. It's disappointing because the scene previous has an interesting take on a familiar device where the heroes are picked up by the villain's head henchman. They even spit out what would have been the most logical conclusion on the way to the finale. To me it felt like when you're caught doing something wrong as a kid, you rattle off too many excuses until one sticks. They go through many possible endings until they find what they think is the best one. I didn't affect the grade too much but after a promising start, Focus didn't quite stick the landing. Critics weren't kind to this movie and while it is solid as a whole, there are missteps. What elevated this movie for me is the efforts of the cast and the excellent first half. I enjoyed the movie for what it is and I believe if you go into it with low expectations, you'll find it's a fun entry into the genre.Good con movie, Multi Racial upgrade of "The Sting" I saw "Focus" in the movie theater and later on cable. Will Smith did a good job and The Australian cutie, Margot Robbie work really well together. They should do a sequel to this movie. It is a modern day "Sting" that starred Robert Redford, Paul Newman, Robert Shaw and co-starred Harold Gould. However the only non white actor in that movie was actor, James Earl Jones' real life dad, Robert Earl Jones in a small supporting role. This version "Focus", I liked for several reasons. 1 The multiracial cast with Asians and Hispanics in supporting roles.  2. I especially love that art imitates real life with the interracial love between Will Smith and really cute, Margot Robbie. They have really good chemistry together. All the scenes in the football 