ollars in cash is just not realistic unless they are in the drug trade. There are several chances to complicate the plot over looked because Smith is hampered by being smitten. There are more than 1 con, and some of the cons are pretty complex, but when you sum it all out the ending with Gerald McRaney is a bit of a disappointment and the reality involving Smith being shot is just not practical. If you like seeing big bags of cash, and good acting it is a great film. But it does have some major draw backs beyond that.Blurred vision There is nothing new about con-men and grifters in film, but the casting of Will Smith and Margot Robbie, certainly creates enough interest. The premise of Smith's character, creating outcomes in his favor "by design" becomes completely implausible. Whilst the first act in New Orleans has some good moments, the final act runs out of steam and becomes a little too far fetched. At no stage do you really buy in to the chemistry between Smith and Robbie, which in the 2nd half of the film, is pretty much the only thing the film is asking you to care about. If you want to see a good film about pickpockets, let me recommend Oliver!Focus (2015) -Focus is a 2015 American romantic comedy-drama film written and directed by Glenn Ficarra and John Requa, starring Will Smith, Margot Robbie, and Rodrigo Santoro. --Filming: -Principal photography began on September 14, 2013 in New Orleans, and moved over to Buenos Aires on November 19, 2013 for three weeks. The last day of shooting in Argentina was on December 10. Filming wrapped in New York City on December 17, 2013. --Critical response: -Focus received mixed reviews from critics. On review aggregator website Rotten Tomatoes, the film has a rating of 56%, based on 181 reviews, with a rating average of 5.8/10. The site's consensus reads, "Focus may have a few too many twists and turns, but it nearly skates by on its glamorous setting and the charm of its stars." On Metacritic, which assigns a normalized 