inded me of many of my Marine friends with his off-color sense of humor. The addition of Gerald McRaney as Owen was also very well done and he completely sold me on his character. Major Dad is always a win in my books. Major Dad Major F'n Dad! Overall, if you like a good heist movie or if you just want to get a good look at Deadshot and Harley together on screen, then go see this movie. It is a good popcorn flick where you can sit back, relax, and enjoy the flick. This isn't a great movie, but a good movie that is worth your money.Kicked off well, kept the momentum, but the end was... It's a Will Smith's movie, anyway, I was going to watch it, but when the initial cast dropped out, followed by a couple more, simply intrigued me. Actually, I enjoyed the film, but did not like it because of the bad ending. It was a good twist, except the shooting thing. An example how a tiny part can decide the entire movie's fate. Well written crime-drama, with a touch of romance. After all the obstacles, the final cast were at their best. Heist movies always excite me because of the involvement of the tricks and thrills. Nicky, a con artist who recruits a small time thief, Jess to work with his gang. When the job and the romance advancing smoothly, an unexpected split happens. So the years passed, when they meet again, what comes is the crux of the remaining story. The first half let us know what kind of character the Nicky is. His overwhelmed dedication for his undertaking and his reliable team's the focus. Overall, it was the best portion of the movie, and the next half goes for the giant kill, but lacks enthusiasm. More like a revenge or jealousy type narration, but only until reaching the climax where it tries being a very clever and happen all the things at a brisk pace. The film was better than I thought, after learning it was criticised, mostly very badly. Would have been a bit better if the writing was cautious for the crucial parts. Importantly, like I said the end part. 'Yes' for the entertainment it provided and 'no' for one of the best products of the year, 6¬Ω/10A decent but lacking con movie. Will Smith's latest film is clever, yet leaving you with the feeling of wanting more from it. Parts are definitely well told and the actual 'conning' certainly brought a smile to my face. However, the problem is that at times it doesn't seem to know what it wants to be. Is it a con film or a love story with stolen watches thrown in? This is where it gets bogged down. On the plus side, as mentioned before, the scamming is definitely the high point of the film with a couple of twists and turns that will either leave you in shock or leave you sat there laughing. The film peaks too early for my liking before finally being dragged to a decent ending. Not the best film you'll see this year but certainly not the worst. A good concept that should have been told better.Focus, from Good to Lame I saw Focus a few days ago, after a friend recommended it to me. I thought, Will Smith, Margo Robbie, awesome thieves, speed and thrill.. Just my type of film. And at first i was amazed. The plot is great, Smith has a talent of playing a d"#khead/Mr.Cool. But further into the film, deeper into the plot i felt that the film started to get a bit over dramatic and lost much of the speed and thrill i found in the beginning.  I give "Focus" 5/10, because of the loss of suspense and to much direction change for me. Lastly i apologize for my English, grammar and stuff like that.  Peace!Will Smith is back and in Great Form, Focus is a great movie with a well developed storyline and a fantastic cast. It's a very enjoyable movie that takes you in straight away, it dosen't waste any time, and I liked that it took this approach, it brought the characters on their journey immediately and developed them throughout instead of providing most of the character development before they head off, it's quite unusual for a movie but I thought they succeeded with it and didn't leave me feeling like either of the two lead characters are underdeveloped, I also thought the ending was a very well written final act, and the twists just kept on coming. The film seemed to have a hard time balancing out between being a crime caper and a romance, I felt like it should have focused on crime much more, it was an interesting story that kept me intrigued, and though I did like the love story, I felt lit didn't necessarily have to be as vital as it was and stall the story as much as it did. Will Smith is back in action here in his first lead role since Men in Black 3 way back in 2012, he is still the charismatic and likable actor that everyone knows and loves him for, and this also goes for Margot Robbie, who stole several scenes and gets to shine as an actress here even more than she did in Wolf of Wall Street, the two made a great pair and were able to make these characters likable, which didn't seem easy as they were very flawed. A slick and well acted crime film, Focus may be forgetful, but it's while it lasts, and I would recommend it to anyone looking for a good drama or romance.  A professional con man takes an amateur under his wing, but a complicated relationship soon blossoms between them.  Best Performance: Will Smith Worst Performance: Adrian MartinezFrequently rewarding, if mostly disappointing caper flic. For the first roughly 40 minutes of "Focus," I had high hopes of a con film on par with "The Sting" and "The Film-Flam Man," a largely-forgotten, minor masterpiece with George C. Scott. Then, "Focus" became as soft and predictable as the "mallow," that is the nickname of one of the characters. What really redeems "Focus" is the chemistry between Will Smith and Margo Robbie. Robbie is a real find; and her chemistry with Smith is most convincingly romantic I have seen in this century. Unfortunately, the sting (pardon the pun) that takes up roughly two-thirds of the movie is utterly predictable and unconvincing. Great production values, fun cast, 